  "aiExplanationFallback": "Your medication list shows two prescribing cascades — situations where one drug's side effect was treated with another drug, rather than addressing the root cause.\n\n**Cascade 1 (3 drugs deep):** Amlodipine, a calcium channel blocker for blood pressure, commonly causes ankle swelling (peripheral edema) — the FDA has received 8,359 reports of this. Furosemide (Lasix) was likely prescribed to treat that swelling. But furosemide raises uric acid levels and triggers gout — confirmed in FDA drug label analysis — leading to allopurinol being prescribed for the gout. One starting drug created a chain of two unnecessary medications.\n\n**Cascade 2:** Lisinopril, an ACE inhibitor, causes a persistent dry cough in 5-35% of patients (8,270 FDA reports). Benzonatate was prescribed to suppress that cough.\n\n**The alternative?** Switching amlodipine to a different blood pressure class eliminates the edema, making furosemide unnecessary, which eliminates the gout, making allopurinol unnecessary. Switching lisinopril to an ARB (like losartan) eliminates the cough, making benzonatate unnecessary. Margaret's 6 medications could become 3.\n\n*This is a screening tool, not medical advice. Please discuss all medication changes with your physician.*"
